1. University of California, Berkeley — SPICE3 / SPICE2 — Core Engine
---------------------------------------------------------------------

Portions of the core simulation engine in src/core/ are translated from UC
Berkeley SPICE3F5 and derive from the earlier SPICE2G6 (1983) Fortran and the
original SPICE / SPICE2 work. This includes the DC operating point, DC sweep,
transient analysis (the MODE / INITF state machine and LTE timestep control),
AC analysis, noise analysis, transfer function, pole-zero, sensitivity, and the
Newton-Raphson convergence aids (e.g. derived from dctran.c, niiter.c, and the
MODE bit definitions in cktdefs.h).

  Copyright 1990 Regents of the University of California.
  All rights reserved.

  Distributed under the permissive BSD-style "Berkeley Spice3" license.

ngspice (maintained SPICE3F5 descendant):

  The maintained SPICE3F5 descendant ngspice is used as the reference
  implementation for neospice. Credit to Paolo Nenzi, Holger Vogt,
  Dietmar Warning, and the ngspice maintainers.

Historical references:

  L. W. Nagel and D. O. Pederson, "SPICE," Memorandum No. ERL-M382,
  UC Berkeley, April 1973.

  L. W. Nagel, "SPICE2: A Computer Program to Simulate Semiconductor
  Circuits," Memorandum No. ERL-M520, UC Berkeley, May 1975.

  SPICE2G6 (1983) and SPICE3F5 (UC Berkeley).


2. Sparse Solver Stack — Sparse 1.3, SuiteSparse AMD / BTF
-----------------------------------------------------------

The sparse solver stack (src/core/neo_solver.cpp, amd.cpp, btf.cpp,
matching.cpp) traces to the following sources.

  The NeoSolver sparse-LU factorization is "Sparse 1.3-compatible." Credit to
  Kenneth S. Kundert and Alberto Sangiovanni-Vincentelli, "Sparse 1.3"
  (UC Berkeley), the sparse-matrix package used by SPICE3.

  The AMD (Approximate Minimum Degree) ordering in amd.cpp derives from and
  matches SuiteSparse AMD by Timothy A. Davis, Patrick Amestoy, and Iain Duff.
  SuiteSparse AMD is BSD-3-Clause licensed.

  The BTF / maximum-transversal logic in btf.cpp and matching.cpp likewise
  traces to Timothy A. Davis's SuiteSparse BTF (BSD-3-Clause licensed).


